04735nam a22005775i 9780226924922DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226924922  a(DE-B1597)524014  a(OCoLC)829713871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPR255b.B27 2015 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a820.9001223  aEC 17002rvk1 aBahr, Arthur, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFragments and Assemblages :bForming Compilations of Medieval London /cArthur Bahr. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Compilation, Assemblage, Fragment -- tChapter One. Civic Counterfactualism and the Assemblage of London. The Corpus of Andrew Horn -- tChapter Two. Fragmentary Forms of Imitative Fantasy. Booklet 3 of the Auchinleck Manuscript -- tChapter Three. Constructing Compilations of Chaucer’s Canterbury Tales -- tChapter Four. Rewriting the Past, Reassembling the Realm. The Trentham Manuscript of John Gower -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Fragments and Assemblages, Arthur Bahr expands the ways in which we interpret medieval manuscripts, examining the formal characteristics of both physical manuscripts and literary works. Specifically, Bahr argues that manuscript compilations from fourteenth-century London reward interpretation as both assemblages and fragments: as meaningfully constructed objects whose forms and textual contents shed light on the city’s literary, social, and political cultures, but also as artifacts whose physical fragmentation invites forms of literary criticism that were unintended by their medieval makers. Such compilations are not simply repositories of data to be used for the reconstruction of the distant past; their physical forms reward literary and aesthetic analysis in their own right. The compilations analyzed reflect the full vibrancy of fourteenth-century London’s literary cultures: the multilingual codices of Edwardian civil servant Andrew Horn and Ricardian poet John Gower, the famous Auchinleck manuscript of texts in Middle English, and Chaucer’s Canterbury Tales. By reading these compilations as both formal shapes and historical occurrences, Bahr uncovers neglected literary histories specific to the time and place of their production. The book offers a less empiricist way of interpreting the relationship between textual and physical form that will be of interest to a wide range of literary critics and manuscript scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xManuscripts. 0aManuscripts, MedievalzEnglandzLondon. 70(DE-601)1062270680(DE-588)4039676-9aMittelenglisch2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-588)4035964-5aLiteratur2gnd 70(DE-601)2139400270(DE-588)4419466-3aSammelhandschrift2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  amedieval, london, manuscripts, literature, 14th century, middle english, auchinleck manuscript, andrew horne, chaucer, john gower, canterbury tales, fantasy, trentham, urban, community, codicology, history, literary, compilers, ricardian poets, formalism, production, religion, nonfiction, cultural studies, theory, criticism, fragments, assemblies, collections.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022692491540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226924922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docume